A: The problem is not with InputStream.read() but with the way you are processing the data. You are processing each byte one by one which is very inefficient. You should process the whole buffer at once.
Here is a simple modification of your code:
byte[] buffer = new byte[1048576];
int i = 0;
int length = -1;

while (true)
{
    int bytesRead = is.read(buffer, i, buffer.length - i);
    if (bytesRead == -1)
    {
        success = false;
        break;
    }

    i += bytesRead;

    if (i >= 4)
    {
        length = buffer[0] | buffer[1] << 8 | buffer[2] << 16 | buffer[3] << 24;
        break;
    }
}

This code reads data into the buffer and processes it in chunks. It also checks if the end of the stream has been reached. If the end of the stream has been reached, it breaks the loop. If the end of the stream has not been reached, it continues to read data into the buffer.
This code assumes that the length of the data is at least 4 bytes. If the length of the data is less than 4 bytes, you will need to handle this case separately.
Also, this code does not handle the case where the length of the data is more than the size of the buffer. You will need to handle this case separately if you expect to receive large amounts of data.

A: You can use the BufferedInputStream to improve the performance of your InputStream.read().
BufferedInputStream is a wrapper class for another input stream (the underlying input stream) that buffers the input data. It reads data from the underlying input stream and stores it in a buffer, which is then provided to the caller of the read() method.
Here is how you can use it:
BufferedInputStream bis = new BufferedInputStream(client.getInputStream());
byte[] buffer = new byte[1048576];
int bytesRead;
while ((bytesRead = bis.read(buffer)) != -1) {
    // Process the data in the buffer
}

This will read data into the buffer and process it in chunks, which will significantly improve the performance.

